The cheap path
Don't manually fix every heading. Instead, use Google Docs' "Paste from Markdown":

Open project-spec/2026-05-04.md (the clean export the script just produced)
Copy all of it
In the Google Doc, select the entire current ProductSpecDoc tab content and delete it
Format → Paste from Markdown (or Cmd+Shift+V once you've enabled the setting)
Google converts as it pastes: # → Heading 1, ## → Heading 2, **bold** → real bold, | Field | Type | tables → native Google tables, etc.
Net result: the Google Doc looks like a proper document, and future exports stay clean.

Caveats worth eyeballing afterwards
A few things might not survive cleanly and are worth a 30-second skim after the paste:

Backslash escapes like created\_at, \=== — these are deliberately in the markdown to prevent Google's exporter from interpreting _ as italic or = as Setext heading. After paste, Google might display them with the backslashes literal. If so, find-and-replace \_ → _ etc. (Or just leave them — they'll look ugly in the Doc but export fine.)
The sentinel marker =============== EndOfProductSpecDoc ================= will probably become a Heading 1 on paste (since markdown sees rows of = as a Setext heading underline). Just unstyle that line back to plain paragraph after pasting.
Per-line indentation on PRD-1.1+ — if those PRDs are still nested in a list in the new pasted version, you'd want to bump them out (Shift+Tab) so they sit at the top level. The "Paste from Markdown" should handle this correctly though, since it goes by markdown structure not visual indent.
